

**Answer: 12168**

**Explanation**

The spiral is formed on a flat‑top hexagonal grid.  
Let the centre (cell 1) have axial coordinates \((0,0)\).  
The six neighbour vectors are  

\[
\begin{aligned}
E &: (1,0), & NE &: (1,-1), & NW &: (0,-1), \\
W &: (-1,0), & SW &: (-1,1), & SE &: (0,1).
\end{aligned}
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1.   Which “ring’’ contains 2026?

For a hexagon of radius \(r\) (distance \(r\) from the centre) the total
number of cells is the centred‑hexagonal number  

\[
H(r)=1+3r(r+1).
\]

\(H(25)=1951\) and \(H(26)=2107\); thus 2026 lies in the ring \(r=26\).

The first cell of this ring is

\[
s=H(25)+1=3\cdot25\cdot26+2=1952,
\]

and its offset inside the ring is  

\[
k=2026-s=74 .
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2.   Coordinates of 2026

For any ring \(r\ge1\) the first cell is at \((1,r-1)\).  
The ring is traversed in the order  

\[
\text{NE }(1,-1),\; \text{NW }(0,-1),\; \text{W }(-1,0),\;
\text{SW }(-1,1),\; \text{SE }(0,1),\; \text{E }(1,0),
\]

with the first (NE) side having length \(r-1\) and the other five sides
length \(r\).

For \(r=26\) the offset \(k=74\) falls in the **west side** (the third
side), whose coordinates are

\[
(x,y)=\bigl(3r-k-1,\,-r\bigr)=\bigl(78-74-1,\,-26\bigr)=(3,-26).
\]

Hence the cell numbered 2026 is at \((3,-26)\).

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3.   The six neighbours

Using the six neighbour vectors:

\[
\begin{array}{ccl}
\text{East}   &:& (4,-26)\\[2pt]
\text{North‑East}&:& (4,-27)\\[2pt]
\text{North‑West}&:& (3,-27)\\[2pt]
\text{West}   &:& (2,-26)\\[2pt]
\text{South‑West}&:& (2,-25)\\[2pt]
\text{South‑East}&:& (3,-25)
\end{array}
\]

Their distances from the centre are  

\[
\begin{array}{c|c}
\text{cell}&\text{ring}\\\hline
(4,-26)&26\\
(4,-27)&27\\
(3,-27)&27\\
(2,-26)&26\\
(2,-25)&25\\
(3,-25)&25
\end{array}
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 4.   Converting the neighbour coordinates back to numbers  

For a cell with radius \(R\) the first number of its ring is  

\[
S(R)=3R(R-1)+2 .
\]

In each ring the offset of a cell on the **west side** (\(y=-R\)) is

\[
\text{offset}=3R-x-1 .
\]

Applying this:

| neighbour | radius \(R\) | offset | number = \(S(R)+\) offset |
|-----------|--------------|--------|---------------------------|
| (4,‑26)   | 26 | \(78-4-1=73\)   | \(1952+73=2025\) |
| (2,‑26)   | 26 | \(78-2-1=75\)   | \(1952+75=2027\) |
| (4,‑27)   | 27 | \(81-4-1=76\)   | \(2108+76=2184\) |
| (3,‑27)   | 27 | \(81-3-1=77\)   | \(2108+77=2185\) |
| (3,‑25)   | 25 | \(75-3-1=71\)   | \(1802+71=1873\) |
| (2,‑25)   | 25 | \(75-2-1=72\)   | \(1802+72=1874\) |

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 5.   Sum of the neighbours

\[
2025+2027+2184+2185+1873+1874 = 12168 .
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
\[
\boxed{12168}
\]
----
